Why Can ISIS Persist?
New York—Deadly terrorist attacks in Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad indicate that the Islamic State (ISIS) has extended its reach to Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and parts of Asia.
The longer ISIS remains strong in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terrorist network will be able to carry out such massacres.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The problem is that the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not regarded ISIS as a primary enemy.
This should have changed.
ISIS has a small fighting force, with the US estimating 20,000 to 25,000 members in Iraq and Syria, and about 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the active military forces of Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is completely insignificant.
In September 2014, President Barack Obama of the United States pledged to "target and ultimately destroy" ISIS, but the United States and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (in the background), have always focused on toppling Syrian President Bashar al-Assad.
Recently, Israeli Army Brigadier General Herzi Halevy openly stated (as relayed to me by a journalist present at Halevy's speech): "Israel does not want to see the situation in Syria end with ISIS being defeated, superpowers leaving the region, and Israel facing a stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but Israel's greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel's two quasi-military adversaries — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on toppling Assad, rather than defeating ISIS.
Influenced by neo-conservatism, for the United States, the Syria war is a continuation of the global American hegemony plan proposed by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz said to U.S. General Wesley Clark:
“But we did learn one thing from the Gulf War, which is that we can use force in the region — in the Middle East — and the Soviets will not stop us.
Before the next superpower challenges us, we have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regimes — Syria, Iran (as stated in the original text), Iraq.”
The United States' multiple wars in the Middle East — Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, and so on — were meant to get the Soviet Union and subsequently Russia out of the competition, allowing the United States to stand alone as a hegemon.
These “efforts” ended in disastrous failures.
For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the primary goal is to overthrow Assad in order to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of a large-scale proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which has unfolded in Syria and Yemen, and also in Bahrain and other countries in the region with divisive tendencies (including Saudi Arabia itself), where the Shia-Sunni confrontation is more intense.
For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional position.
But Turkey now faces three opponents along its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
So far, ISIS has been less important to Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
But terrorist attacks in Turkey orchestrated by ISIS may change this situation.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests, achieving them through proxy wars and supporting quasi-military actions.
However, both countries have expressed willingness to cooperate with the United States in combating ISIS, and they can also cooperate on other issues.
So far, the United States has remained indifferent because its focus is on toppling Assad.
The U.S. foreign policy establishment condemns Russian President Putin for backing Assad, while Russia condemns the United States for trying to overthrow Assad.
These complaints appear to be directly opposed, but they are not actually so.
The attempts by the United States and its allies to overthrow Assad violate the United Nations Charter, while Russia's support for Assad aligns with Syria's right to self-defense as stipulated in the Charter.
Indeed, Assad is a tyrant, but the United Nations Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
The persistent existence of ISIS highlights three major strategic flaws in U.S. foreign policy, as well as one fatal tactical flaw.
First, the neo-conservative demand to achieve American hegemony through regime change is not only an ignorant view of bloody thinking; it is also a classic case of imperial overreach.
Everywhere the United States has attempted this, it has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Second, the CIA has long armed and trained Sunni jihadists through secret operations funded by Saudi Arabia.
In turn, these jihadists gave rise to ISIS, which is the direct (perhaps unintended) consequence of the policies pursued by the CIA and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, viewing Iran and Russia as irreconcilable enemies of the United States is largely a self-fulfilling outdated prophecy.
Rebuilding relations with both countries is possible.
Fourth, tactically, the United States has failed in its attempt to win a two-front war against Assad and ISIS.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and the al-Nusira Front, will fill the vacuum.
If the United States, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide air cover and logistical support, Assad and his Iraqi allies could defeat ISIS.
Indeed, Assad will continue to hold power; indeed, Russia will continue to be Syria's ally; indeed, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue, perhaps still under the banner of ISIS for a period of time; but the organization will be driven out of its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
This outcome would not only eradicate ISIS from the Middle East, but also lay the foundation for a more comprehensive relief of regional tensions.
The United States and Russia could begin to reverse the recent new Cold War by jointly expelling jihadist terrorism.
(NATO's commitment to not allow Ukraine to join or not escalate ballistic missile defense in Eastern Europe could also be beneficial.)
There are other benefits as well.
Adopting a cooperative approach to combating ISIS would give Saudi Arabia and Turkey the reason and opportunity to seek new temporary arrangements with Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened by allowing Iran to build cooperative economic and geopolitical relations with the West, thereby increasing the opportunity for the long-delayed Israeli-Palestinian reconciliation in turn.
The rise of ISIS is a manifestation of the current strategic flaws of the West — especially the United States.
The West is capable of defeating ISIS.
The issue is whether the United States will carry out the strategic reassessment required to achieve this goal.
